I have an example Ted Bailey wrote ages ago (attached), but he doesn't explain
how the parameters are used. And it's not what I thought they'd be, it looks
like they are the "difference from the normal". Yeah, I've just checked
the lib source, and they are indeed the difference from the norm.

DisplayAdjust #coplist,fetchwid,ddfstrt,ddfstop,diwstrt,diwstop

#coplist - the number of your coplist object
fetchwid - fetch width - 32 for fetchmode 3 I think
ddfstrt - data fetch start (what horizontal position in the scanline the
data is starting to be read from memory by the custom chips)
ddfstop - stop position for data fetch
diwstrt - display window start (left edge of the display)
diwstop - display window stop (right edge of display)

I also think the ddfxxxx values are in multiples of 4, so if you specify
e.g. 8 you actually change the start/stop position by 32 pixels (this is
the way the hardware works).

If you wanted to move the things to left (as in your case) you would
specify something like:

DisplayAdjust 0,0,-8,-8,-16,-16
Would move the data fetch 32 pixels to the left and the window 16 pixels
to the left. You need to start the data fetch before the display window,
but that will already be the case, so if you move them to the left in
equal amounts, you should be OK.

And I'm guessing here. And it may be offset to the right for a good reason
 - that all the stuff you have (sprites and fetchmode and stuff) means you
cannot position the display any further to the left, due to hardware
limitations. You might also need to move them in multiples of 32 due to
the fetchmode working in multiples of 32 on fetchmode 3.

